# Search API Reference

## Overview

The Redis Search service provides multiple endpoints for searching across media content. Results are sourced from two types of backends:

- **Indexed (RediSearch)**: tv, movie, person, podcast, author, book
- **Brokered (Redis-cached APIs)**: artist, album, video, news, ratings

## Endpoints

### 1. Autocomplete (JSON)

```
GET /api/autocomplete?q={query}&sources={sources}
```

**Parameters:**
| Parameter | Type | Required | Description |
|-----------|------|----------|-------------|
| `q` | string | Yes | Search query (min 2 characters). May include source keywords (e.g., "movie", "podcast") when sources not specified; see Query Source Hints. |
| `sources` | string | No | Comma-separated list of sources to search |
| `raw` | bool | No | If true, treat `q` as raw RediSearch syntax (disables source hint parsing) |

**Valid Sources:** `tv`, `movie`, `person`, `podcast`, `author`, `book`, `news`, `video`, `ratings`, `artist`, `album`

**Example:**
```
/api/autocomplete?q=breaking+bad
/api/autocomplete?q=beatles&sources=artist,album
/api/autocomplete?q=matrix&sources=tv,movie
```

**Response:** JSON object with results grouped by source type. When a source hint was applied, includes `source_hint` (array of source names).

**Media ranking behavior:**
- When `tv` and/or `movie` are requested, Redis is queried per media source bucket, not as one shared mixed media pool.
- `limit` applies per requested source (`tv`, `movie`, etc.), not across a combined movie+tv candidate set.
- This prevents high-popularity movie keyword matches from crowding out exact-title TV hits before Python re-ranking runs.

---

### 1b. Autocomplete Minimal (Lightweight / Projected)

```
GET /api/autocomplete/minimal?q={query}&sources={sources}&limit={limit}&fields={fields}
```

**Parameters:**
| Parameter | Type | Required | Default | Description |
|-----------|------|----------|---------|-------------|
| `q` | string | Yes | — | Search query (min 2 characters) |
| `sources` | string | No | `tv,movie` | Comma-separated indexed sources: tv, movie, person, podcast, author, book |
| `limit` | int | No | 10 | Max results per source (1–50) |
| `fields` | string | No | default set | Comma-separated field names to return per result. `mc_id` and `mc_type` are always included. |

**Default fields** (when `fields` omitted): `mc_id`, `mc_type`, `search_title`, `year`, `poster_path`, `popularity`, `image`

**Allowed fields:** `mc_id`, `mc_type`, `mc_subtype`, `search_title`, `title`, `name`, `year`, `poster_path`, `image`, `backdrop_path`, `popularity`, `rating`, `overview`, `author`, `first_publish_year`, `source_id`, `source`, `genre_ids`, `genres`, `release_date`, `first_air_date`, `known_for_department`, `episode_count`, `known_for_titles`, `origin_country`, `original_language`, `us_rating`, `also_known_as`, `author_name`

**Example:**
```
/api/autocomplete/minimal?q=matrix&sources=movie,tv&limit=12&fields=mc_id,mc_type,search_title,year,poster_path
/api/autocomplete/minimal?q=brad&sources=person&fields=mc_id,search_title,image
/api/autocomplete/minimal?q=serial&sources=podcast&limit=5
```

**Performance characteristics:**
- Uses Redis `RETURN` field projection — only requested fields are transferred from the index.
- No full JSON document parsing or Python re-ranking. Redis handles sorting (popularity desc).
- No brokered API calls — only indexed sources supported.
- Response is grouped by source: `{ "tv": [...], "movie": [...] }`.

