### 1c. Resolve (Exact-Match Disambiguation)

```
GET /api/resolve?q={title}&sources={sources}&fields={fields}&full={full}&near_misses={n}
```

Returns **all** tier 0-1 exact-match entities for a fully-formed title, ranked by the standard scoring (popularity / recency). Use this when the caller needs to confirm an exact title or disambiguate between multiple entities sharing the same name (e.g. "The Godfather" 1972 vs 1990).

When `near_misses` > 0 and no exact matches are found, the response includes the top N best-ranked candidates that were not exact matches, enabling "Did you mean?" UX. Uses a two-pass strategy: first tries the standard prefix query, then falls back to RediSearch fuzzy matching (Levenshtein distance 1) if the prefix query returned nothing. Fuzzy results are ranked by edit distance to the query (stopwords stripped) with popularity as tiebreaker.

**Parameters:**
| Parameter | Type | Required | Default | Description |
|-----------|------|----------|---------|-------------|
| `q` | string | Yes | — | Fully-formed title to resolve (min 2 characters) |
| `sources` | string | No | `tv,movie` | Comma-separated indexed sources: tv, movie, person, podcast, author, book |
| `fields` | string | No | default set | Comma-separated extra field names to include per match. Ignored when `full=true`. |
| `full` | bool | No | `false` | When true, return the complete Redis document for each match. |
| `near_misses` | int | No | `0` | When > 0 and no exact matches found, return up to this many best-ranked near-miss candidates. Range: 0–10. |

**Default fields** (always included): `mc_id`, `mc_type`, `title`, `search_title`, `release_date`, `first_air_date`, `last_aired_date`

**Allowed extra fields:** Same allowlist as `/api/autocomplete/minimal` — `poster_path`, `year`, `popularity`, `rating`, `overview`, `genre_ids`, `genres`, `source_id`, `source`, etc.

**Response shape:**
```json
{
    "query": "The Godfather",
    "matches": [
        { "mc_id": "tmdb_238", "mc_type": "movie", "title": "The Godfather", "release_date": "1972-03-14", ... },
        { "mc_id": "tmdb_240", "mc_type": "movie", "title": "The Godfather Part II", ... }
    ],
    "near_misses": [],
    "total": 2,
    "latency_ms": 12.3
}
```

When no exact matches exist and `near_misses` > 0:
```json
{
    "query": "Godfater",
    "matches": [],
    "near_misses": [
        { "mc_id": "tmdb_238", "mc_type": "movie", "source": "movie", "search_title": "The Godfather", ... },
        { "mc_id": "tmdb_240", "mc_type": "movie", "source": "movie", "search_title": "The Godfather Part II", ... }
    ],
    "total": 0,
    "latency_ms": 14.1
}
```

**Key differences from `/api/autocomplete`:**
- Returns a flat `matches` array, not grouped by source.
- Returns **all** exact matches, not just one `exact_match` winner.
- Only searches indexed sources (no brokered APIs).
- Supports `full=true` to return complete Redis documents.
- Supports `near_misses` for fallback suggestions when no exact match is found.

**Example:**
```
/api/resolve?q=the+godfather&sources=movie
/api/resolve?q=breaking+bad&sources=tv,movie
/api/resolve?q=brad+pitt&sources=person&fields=popularity,image
/api/resolve?q=the+godfather&sources=movie&full=true
/api/resolve?q=godfater&sources=movie&near_misses=2
```

**Web UI:** The **Direct Match** toggle in the search bar activates resolve mode. When ON, autocomplete and search are suppressed; Enter calls `/api/resolve` with the active source filters and `near_misses=2`. Results are grouped by `mc_type` and rendered using the standard card layout. When no exact match is found, near misses render under a "Did you mean?" header with amber styling.

